			p School districts still have tools they can use to integrate, including creating magnet programs and charter schools, and redrawing school boundary lines. But small, voluntary steps like these in Maryland have proved almost impossible to execute.

			p Baltimore County — the largest school district in the region, with 112,000 students and an increasingly diverse population — could be a leader in integration. But at the time of the redistricting, there were six new members on the county school board and Dance’s contract was up for renewal. He didn’t feel that he could force the issue.

			p The school board, meanwhile, didn’t make integration a priority, and there was no push from the community to take it on.

			p That meant the question of diversity was essentially turned over to the committee of about 45 people, most of them parents.

			p As the process unfolded, redrawing the boundary lines exposed fault lines between their communities.

			p “It was like, they were fighting to keep what they got, and we were fighting to keep what we got,” Sanford said, “instead of us fighting to figure out how to make what we had better.”

