			p Sanford thought that the portable classrooms were a safety risk and an eyesore in a community where he and others paid property taxes for their well-maintained, single-family homes.

			p He and other Johnnycake parents began the redistricting process thinking about how to improve student-teacher ratios and get the children out of the trailers and back into the main school building.

			p On the south side of Route 40 in Catonsville were four aging, crowded schools made up of predominantly white families whose PTAs had come together for years to fight for renovations and more space. These parents from Westchester, Hillcrest, Westowne and Catonsville elementaries had in many cases paid a premium for their houses so they could ensure that their children were in some of the best schools in the county.

			p Hillcrest, for example, is 68 percent white. A quarter of its students received subsidized lunches. About half of fifth-graders passed the English tests. Fifty-nine percent passed math.

			p Hillcrest parents loved that they could walk their children to school in a closely knit community. Construction had already begun on the new Catonsville and Westowne schools, and parents saw redistricting as the final step in their winning battle before they moved into the new buildings the next year.

			p Parents said they didn’t want their children to have to cross busy U.S. 40 to go to school, or to be moved to schools they saw as inferior.

			p James Kitchel, a Hillcrest father, said he didn’t expect when he walked into the cafeteria at Catonsville High School on a hot September night that he would be confronted with parents from many other schools. He and other parents thought it would just be their four schools redrawing a few lines.

			p Integration wasn’t what they had fought for, or thought about.

	.article__chapter-title
		.article__chapter-title__text ‘We’re going to defend this spot’

	p.chapterIntro When the consultant presented options for the new boundary lines in September, it didn’t take long for feelings to get raw.
	
	.container.container--article
		.article

			p Video of the meetings was posted on a website. Parents and others could comment on the site’s public email forum, where comments could be read by anyone. Those emails — in the end, the printout totaled 145 pages — quickly became a barometer of the parents’ perspectives.

			p By the end of September, proposals that moved students from more affluent, white neighborhoods north across U.S. 40 and into Johnnycake and Edmondson Heights caused a storm of protest.

			p “You are potentially causing our property values in Academy Heights to plummet!” one parent wrote in an email. “This is unacceptable Baltimore County. ... Are you punishing Westowne families for wanting a better school? You should be ashamed of yourselves. ... Keep Catonsville in Catonsville. Bring affluent families to Westowne.”

			p Another parent wrote: “If my child has to cross Route 40 to attend school next year, she will be going to a private school . ... The parents at Westowne have worked hard over the last few years to improve the environment of our school and to have to give that up to attend a lower ranking school is unacceptable.”

			figure.inline-media.inline-media--borderLeft.inline-media--pullquote.inline-media--big(data-sr)
				.inline-media--pullquote__text &ldquo;I felt as though we didn’t live on that side of Catonsville, so they didn’t want us on that side of Catonsville.&rdquo;
				.inline-media--pullquote__src Jeff Sanford, an African-American father of twin boys at Johnnycake Elementary School

			p The retorts from the parents on the other side of U.S. 40 poured in.

			p “Wow! Hope my Ed Heights child doesn’t ruin yours,” one mother wrote on a Facebook post. “How exactly do you quantify a ‘lower standard of education’? Perhaps the almighty rating will rise if more involved parents became a part of the school community, but the ‘Catonsville’ parents need to stop talking about this issue as if we are some disease to be avoided.”

			p Johnnycake representative Obi Linton, the father of three children in the school, has lived in Catonsville for 19 years. He didn’t expect that reaction from a community that he knew as warm and friendly at the farmers’ market, the annual holiday parade and the tree-lighting ceremony.

			p Sanford was disturbed. He saw the language, looked at his 11-year old twin sons and thought how little had changed since Jim Crow.

			p “Is this what they have to deal with?” he thought. “This ain’t the ’40s and ’50s.”

			p From the moment the consultant, Cropper, presented the oversized maps outlining options, Sanford said, it became clear that working for the good of all children wasn’t the primary goal.

