			p Some research suggests that once a school has more than 40 percent of its students living in poverty, achievement starts to drop off.

			p “Honestly, it is hard to hold it against parents,” said Erica Mah, an Asian-American Hillcrest parent. “They are looking at what is going to happen to my child, and not the greater good.”

			p Parents said they feared their children’s education would suffer if students weren’t being pushed to perform at the highest levels.
			
			figure.inline-media.inline-media--borderLeft.inline-media--pullquote.inline-media--small(data-sr)
				.inline-media--pullquote__text &ldquo;Honestly, it is hard to hold it against parents. They are looking at what is going to happen to my child, and not the greater good.&rdquo;
				.inline-media--pullquote__src Erica Mah, an Asian-American Hillcrest parent

			p The parents’ worries were not baseless. The highest-performing schools are usually those with the wealthiest families. The percentage of Hillcrest fifth-graders who passed state standardized tests in 2016 in English and math was double that at Johnnycake. And the Hillcrest families were wealthier.

			p Parents at Westowne said in interviews that their school was a model for integration. About half of its students were black and Latino, and 46 percent qualified for a free or reduced-price meal. But when the idea of moving half of Westowne’s students out was floated as an option, parents fought back.

			p PTA president Justine Stull, who is white, said she had moved to her neighborhood in part because she believed her children would benefit from the diversity. But she worried that adding more minority children could tip the balance in her kids’ classrooms, burdening them with students who needed extra help.

			p “There is an overlap between race, poverty and childhood trauma,” she said. “They have learning issues that lead to behavioral struggles, behavioral needs.”

			p She was concerned about the impact of other students' behavior on her own children's learning.

			p “We don’t want to talk about these things,” Stull said. “They are too hard.”

	figure.media-package
		.media-package__img--left
